def listToString(s):  
    
    # initialize an empty string 
    strr = ""  
    
    # traverse in the string   
    for i in s:  
        strr += i  
    
    # return string   
    return strr

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 105002 loans in the dataset with 13 features (Term ,LoanStatus ,BorrowerRate ,LenderYield ,ProsperScore,ListingCategory (numeric),EmploymentStatus,LoanOriginalAmount,EstimatedLoss,EstimatedReturn,IncomeVerifiable). Most variables are numeric in nature and the variables LoanStatus , Occupation and EmploymentStatus is object datatype but ProsperScore and Term are ordered variable with the following levels.

ProsperScore : 1 , 2 , 3 ... , 10
Term : 12 , 36 , 60

and The category of the listing that the borrower selected when posting their listing:
0 - Not Available 11 - Engagement Ring
1 - Debt Consolidation 12 - Green Loans
2 - Home Improvement 13 - Household Expenses
3 - Business 14 - Large Purchases
4 - Personal Loan 15 - Medical/Dental
5 - Student Use 16 - Motorcycle
6 - Auto 17 - RV
7- Other 18 - Taxes
8 - Baby&Adoption 19 - Vacation
9 - Boat 20 - Wedding Loans
10 - Cosmetic Procedure

and i make a new colomn to help me LoanStatusNum with the following levels

0---> Cancelled
1---> Completed
2---> Current
3---> PastDue
4----> Defaulted
5----> Chargedoff
6----> FinalPaymentInProgress


IncomeVerifiable:True or False

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I'm most interested in what features are best for predicting Loan amount and Status

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

BorrowerAPR ,BorrowerRate ,LenderYield ,ProsperScore and ListingCategory

# plot matrix of numeric features against categorical features.

np.random.seed(45)

samples = np.random.choice(df.shape[0], 20000, replace = False)
df_samp = df.iloc[samples,:]


def boxplot(x, y, **kwargs):
    
    plt.xticks(rotation = 45)
    sb.boxplot(x, y, color = color)


g = sb.PairGrid(data = df_samp, y_vars = quan_vars , x_vars = ['LoanStatus','Term' ,'EmploymentStatus','ProsperScore','IncomeVerifiable'],
                size = 3, aspect = 1.5)
g.map(boxplot)
plt.subplots_adjust(top=0.9)
g.fig.suptitle('plot numeric features against categorical features');

# compute the logarithm of numbers to make multivariate plotting easier
def log_trans(x, inverse = False):

    if not inverse:
        return np.log10(x)
    else:
        return np.power(10, x)

def hist2dgrid(x, y,log = False ,**kwargs):
   
    palette = kwargs.pop('color')

    if log:
        bins_x = log_trans(np.arange(log_trans(df.LoanOriginalAmount.min()), log_trans(df.LoanOriginalAmount.max())+0.1,0.1),True)
        bins_y = np.arange(0.03,0.34+0.02, 0.02)
        plt.hist2d(x, y, bins = [bins_x, bins_y], cmap = palette, cmin = 0.5)
        plt.xscale('log')
        plt.xticks([1e3, 2e3, 5e3, 1e4, 2e4 ,3e4],[ '1k', '2k', '5k', '10k', '20k','30k'])
            
    else:
        bins_x = np.arange(0.03,0.34+0.02, 0.02)
        bins_y = np.arange(0,0.28+0.02, 0.02)
        plt.hist2d(x, y, bins = [bins_x, bins_y], cmap = palette, cmin = 0.5)
